{{About|the present-day newspaper of the Latvian diaspora in Europe|the wartime resistance newspaper|Brīvā Latvija (1943-44)}}
{{Infobox Newspaper | name = Brīvā Latvija | image = Brīvā_Latvija_header.png | image_size = 300px | caption = [[Masthead (publishing)|masthead]] | type = weekly [[newspaper]] | format = tabloid | foundation = 1986 | ceased publication = | price = [[Lats|Ls]] 0.40 in [[Latvia]], varies elsewhere | owners = Latvian Publishers Association | publisher = ELPA | editor = Ligita Kovtuna | chiefeditor = | assoceditor = | staff = | language = [[Latvian language|Latvian]] | political = | circulation = | headquarters = [[Riga]], Latvia, and [[Catthorpe]], Leics., UK | oclc = | ISSN = 0934-6759 | website = [http://www.brivalatvija.lv www.brivalatvija.lv] }}
'''''Brīvā Latvija''''' (Free Latvia; {{ISSN|0934-6759}}) is a weekly newspaper for [[Latvian people|Latvians]] living outside [[Latvia]], aimed mainly at those residing in western Europe. It was founded in 1986 through the merger of two [[émigré]] newspapers: the UK-based ''Londonas Avīze'' (London News; founded 1942) and ''Latvija'' (Latvia; founded 1946 in postwar [[Displaced person|DP]] camps), based in [[West Germany]]. ''BL'' is co-owned by the Latvian communities of western Europe. The Latvian communities in Britain, Germany, and Sweden each provide members for the newspaper's board. In the mid-1990s, after Latvia regained its independence, the printing of ''BL'' was moved for economic reasons to [[Riga]], where the editorial office also later moved.
