{{refimprove|date=October 2013}} {{Infobox former country |conventional_long_name = Republic of the North Solomons |common_name = North Solomons |image_flag = Flag of Bougainville.svg |image_map = North solomons.png |continent = Oceania |country = Papua New Guinea |status = Unrecognized |status_type = [[List of states with limited recognition|Unrecognised state]] |p1 = Territory of Papua and New Guinea |flag_p1 = Flag_of_Papua_New_Guinea_1970.svg |s1 = Papua New Guinea |flag_s1 = Flag of Papua New Guinea.svg |s2 = Autonomous Region of Bougainville |flag_s2 = Flag of Bougainville.svg |life_span = 1975&ndash;1976 |government_type = Republic |title_leader = President/Chairman |leader1 = [[Alexis Sarei]] (President)/[[John Momis]] (Chairman) |year_leader1 = 1975&ndash;1976 |capital = [[Buka, Papua New Guinea|Buka]] |event_start = Declared |year_start = 1975 |year_end = 1976 |date_start = 1 September |event1 = Reintegrated into Papua New Guinea as "North Solomons Province" |date_event1 = 9 August 1976<ref>{{cite book|last1=Notholt|first1=Stuart A.|title=Fields of Fire - An Atlas of Ethnic Conflict|date=December 2009|page=6.27|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=r7SSlQJMsbsC&pg=SA6-PA27&lpg=SA6-PA27&#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref> }}
The '''Republic of the North Solomons''' was an [[list of states with limited recognition|unrecognised state]] that purported to exist for about six months in what is now the [[Autonomous Region of Bougainville]], [[Papua New Guinea]] (PNG). It involved:<ref name="ReferenceA">The Bougainville independence referendum: Assessing the risks and challenges before, during and after the referendum by Jo Woodbury January 2015; Commonwealth of Australia</ref><ref>Other People's Wars: A History of Australian Peacekeeping; Peter Londey; Allen & Unwin, 2004; Laracy 'Bougainville secessionism'</ref>
{{quote|a 'Unilateral Declaration of Independence of the Republic of North Solomons' and a failed bid for self-determination at the [[UN]]}}
Independence was [[Unilateralism|unilaterally]] declared on 1 September 1975,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Notholt|first1=Stuart A.|title=Fields of Fire - An Atlas of Ethnic Conflict|date=December 2009|page=6.27|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=r7SSlQJMsbsC&pg=SA6-PA27&lpg=SA6-PA27&#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref> from the [[Australia]]n-administered [[territory of Papua and New Guinea]], which itself was due to become independent on 16 September.
Tensions soon escalated and by mid-1976, the Papua New Guinea riot police squad was sent to southern Bougainville to restore order.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> [[John Momis]], at the time Chairman of the putative Republic's ruling council denounced this action as an invasion.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>
Mutual concerns about security on the island and the Republic's failure to achieve any international recognition eventually led to talks between the PNG Government and the secessionist leader.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> A settlement was reached in August 1976 on the basis of increased decentralisation. Bougainville was renamed "''North Solomons Province''", in recognition of its geography, and re-absorbed politically into PNG with increased self-governance powers, a model later replicated to delineate provincial powers throughout PNG.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>
==Reaction== Papua New Guinea's Chief Minister, Mr [[Michael Somare]], initially showed no outward concern at Bougainville's stand. The [[Roman Catholic Church]], the most powerful organization in Bougainville, officially announced its support for the breakaway move.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}} (Bougainvilleans have experienced [[German Colonial Empire|German]], [[British Empire|British]], and [[Australia]]n [[Colony|colonial administrations]] and [[Missionary|missionaries]].) Papua New Guinea, Australia and the [[United Nations]] did not recognize the [[secession]] and PNG government officials on the island simply ignored it. Through their district council, the Western Islands District of the [[British Solomon Islands Protectorate]]{{spaced ndash}}comprising a third of the population of the [[Solomon Islands]]{{spaced ndash}}asked to join independent Bougainville.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}
==Context== Many Bougainville islanders have always regarded themselves as a separate entity in Papua New Guinea.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}} The people have very dark skin in contrast to the lighter skin colour of Papuans.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> The island is over 900 [[kilometre]]s east of the [[Geography of Papua New Guinea|mainland]] and, geographically, is nearer the [[Solomon Islands]], forming part of the [[Solomon Islands (archipelago)|Solomon Islands archipelago]].<ref name="ReferenceA"/>
The declaration of independence followed the discovery sometime previously of the world's largest [[Mineral|deposit]]s of [[copper]] in the region. The Papua New Guinea Government had then established the [[Bougainville Copper]] mine company in [[Panguna]], central Bougainville. Bougainville Copper was a subsidiary of [[Consolidated Zinc|Conzinc Rio Tinto of Australia]], which in turn was controlled by the British company [[Rio Tinto Group]]. When the [[mining]] started, the Australian administration, backed by [[Paramilitary|armed police]], gave access to [[Prospecting|prospectors]] while informing residents that their land was being taken over without discussion.
